4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, a person commits the crime
6 of unlawful possession of marijuana in the first degree
7 if he or she possesses marijuana for other than
8 personal use or possesses marijuana for personal use
9 only after having been previously convicted of unlawful
10 possession in the second degree or unlawful possession
11 of marijuana for his or her personal use only.
12 This bill would amend the crime of unlawful
13 possession of marijuana in the first degree to provide
14 that a person commits the crime if he or she possesses
15 one or more ounces of marijuana and would prescribe new
16 criminal penalties based on the number of prior
17 violations.
18 Under existing law, a person commits the crime
19 of unlawful possession of marijuana in the second
20 degree if he or she possesses marijuana for personal
21 use only. Existing law also provides that the crime of
22 unlawful possession of marijuana in the second degree
23 is a Class A misdemeanor.
24 This bill would amend the crime of unlawful
25 possession of marijuana in the second degree to provide
26 that a person commits the crime if he or she possesses
27 less than one ounce of marijuana and would reduce the
28 criminal penalty to a violation, punishable by a fine.
Page 1

criminal penalty to a violation, punishable by a fine.
SB285 INTRODUCED
29 This bill would also provide that a person who
30 is charged with, found not guilty of, or convicted of
31 unlawful possession of marijuana in the first or second
32 degree may have that charge, finding, or conviction
33 expunged if he or she has not been convicted of a
34 felony, misdemeanor, or violation, excluding minor
35 traffic violations, within the last five years.
36
